A well-packed dirt path leads from the dense jungle to the north to aclearing nearby to the west.  Here, and off into the distance to the northand west, large, round, white marker stones can be seen on the edge of thepath.  An image of the fertile moon goddess has been carved into the granitestone here.

A well-packed mud path leads from the dense jungle to the south to aclearing to the north.  Here, and off into the distance to the south, yousee large, round, white marker stones on the edge of the path.  An image ofthe all powerful lifegiver, the sun, has been carved into the granite stonehere.

The trees part as you step forth, revealing a wide river with a largeisland city.  A wide, brightly painted, stone platform lies before you,spanning the river.  Down at the end of the platform figures move, made tinyby the distance.  Beyond the platform tall pyramids dominate the island.White smoke rises from somewhere in the city, and the strange, disquietingsmell of charred flesh drifts over to you.

Rooms.RoomName: A Small Clearing in the Jungle
Rooms.RoomDescription: Stepping through a gap in the dense greenery, you reach a small sunlitclearing.  A large insect buzzes past your head, and a bright bird dartsafter it.  To the north you hear a faint sound, rising and falling, perhapsthe sound of someone's voice.

A beautiful flowering tree stands here filling the air with a heavenlyscent.  Its smooth grey trunk rises up to spreading branches where bright,red, trumpet-shaped flowers hang down between deep green leaves.  Somethingbright moves in and out of sight, up in the foliage.

The canopy of towering trees draws closed high above you.  Sun filteringthrough the leaves tints the air green.  With each step you hear rustlingmovement all around you, as wild creatures scurry to get out of your way.

Looking up into the forest canopy as the sun shines down through theleaves, one is assailed with a multitude of shades of green.  The thickfoliage surrounding you seems barren of life although in fact it sheltersthousands of harmless and not-so-harmless creatures.

A shiver runs through you as you step forward, with the feeling that eyesare following you.  A strange pungent scent fills the air, making you thinkof...  Wait...  What was that?  Did you see a pair of `kyellow`c eyes blinkat you through the leaves?  ``

You step onto a wide stone platform bridging the river.  Low walls oneither side are carved with great skill and detail.  Looking closer you seebrightly painted green serpent-forms undulating along the walls' length.Their obsidan eyes glitter, seeming almost alive.  Surrounding the carvenserpents is a pale mosiaic of seashells.  A bright motion captures yourattention: down toward the city guards are patrolling, their featherdheadresses more colorful than even the surrounding jungle.

The slope of the bank is so gentle here that you can easily climb in and outof the river.  The water is brown and opaque, but you see glints ofdarting `osilver`g forms as you stare into the river's depths.``

`cGreen tree branches`g arch over the river here, and gnarly roots extendout into the water catching passing debris.  Something curved and whitecatches your eye from among the massed twigs and dead leaves.  Leaningcloser you feel a shudder run through you as you recongnize it to be a`bhuman's hip bone``.

To the west `hwhite smoke `grises from the circular `m`dTemple of theMoon`g.  Eastward the river flows onward, around a bend and out of sight.Far above you an eagle circles, and screams- the wild call making youshiver.  ``

The river runs wide and slow here; the water's `amurky depths `gseem somehow toswirl and churn.  Fascinated, you gaze downward, sensing a strange powercalling to you from below.  Almost beyond perception you see `csomething `gonthe river's floor.``

A small dock extends toward you across the river from the southern bank. Afew reed canoes float alongside it.  Beyond the dock a wide, low buildingstands, with excited crowds milling about it.  Perhaps there is some sort offestival today?

Rivulets of `bcrimson blood `gflow down the side of the `dTemple of the `kSun`gto the south.  Bright against the dull stone wall, the blood cascadesdown a channel into the river around you, staining the water `ablack`g.  Soundsof wailing and chanting intermingle and drift to your ears, confused andmeaningless.``

The river current picks up speed here as the water is constricted betweenthe island and the bank.  Along the northern shore a clump of green riverreeds sways and rustles in the breeze.  To the west, thick tall reeds clogthe river, making it impassible.

To the west the river continues, wide and curving.  You can't see where itleads as it bends away into the dense jungle covering both banks.  To the eastthe river parts around an island city, its stone pyramids taller than eventhe towering jungle canopy.

Rooms.RoomName: On the River, Behind the Palace
Rooms.RoomDescription: Travelling around the island city you now see the back of the King's palace.The carved image of the Rain God glares down at you from its high spot on thewall's face.  Atop the palace roof the patrolling guards notice your arrival.They all turn and watch your progress calmly.

Sunlight sparkles on the river's brown ripples, dazzlingly bright.  Waveslap gently against the island to the northeast.  A cloud of tiny gnats meandersover the water to you and begins to buzz around your head.

The warm water of the river has been stopped up by the roots of hundredsof tall trees growing in the shallow water.  Tiny fish flit about betweenthe thick, brown roots.  Above and nearby to the east, a large wooden bridgecovers the outlet to the river.

`d`eDeep shadow`g covers the water here, as you drift under the bridge that leads tothe city.  Above you the stonework glistens, slimy and `ablack`g with ages of damp.The lapping river, previously quiet, now echoes all about you.  Even so, youthink you can hear something moving on the bridge above.``

Rooms.RoomName: At the Bottom of the River
Rooms.RoomDescription: Wan light feebly shines through the muddy depths, barely providing enoughillumination to see by.  A dim shape, too sharp edged to be natural, sticksout from the soft mud of the river's bottom.  As you move in for a closerlook, small fish dart away.  You see a stone box, with a top of inlaid goldand turquoise.  The symbol of a rising sun becomes clear when you wipe themud away.

You are just barely able to pick your way between the towering jungletrees.  North of you you catch a glimpse of a `dpathway`c.  To either sidethe verdant foliage blocks your view, but you hear wild calls all around,and sense movement in the branches.  Something lives out there.  West standsa small `npool of water `cwhich leads off into a small river to thenorth-west.  ``

Rooms.RoomName: A Narrow Path in the Jungle
Rooms.RoomDescription: It seems that the light grows a little brighter through the trees to thenorth, and you think you hear the sound of rushing water that way.The path continues south and north, and to either side, dense jungletowers over you.

Tall trees tower over you here, making you feel very tiny in comparison.A faint game trail can be seen on the ground leading from the north to thewest.  A rustle from the undergrowth instantly sets you on your guard.

The thick, dense foliage can not be pirced by your gaze.  Tall treestower overhead, veiling the bright, hot sun and creating a kaleidoscope ofgreens upon the jungle floor.  A rustle in the nearby underbrush instantlysets you on your guard.

Tiny flowers grow here in a rainbow of colors.  Tropical birds gracefullyfly past you, chirping a variety of musical notes.  A cool, refreshingbreeze blows through the trees and you hear a nearby rustle.  That was thewind, wasn't it?

The canopy of towering trees draws closed high above you.  Sun filteringthrough the leaves tints the air green.  With each step you hear rustlingmovement all around you, as wild creatures scurry to get out of your way.

A clearly defined path of packed dirt leads from the north to the eastthrough the dense, overhanging trees.  Here, and off into the distancenorthward and eastward, large, round marker stones on the edge of the pathcan be seen.  An image of the wise spider god has been carved into thegranite stone here.
`gThis small canoe has been formed by hollowing out a large log.  There'sjust room enough for one person and a few things.  ``

Rooms.RoomDescription: Nearby to the south is the stone platform that crosses the river,connecting the island city to the mainland.  North and west quiet streetsextend, small houses lining both sides.

This section of the city has recently been built up and paved.  Along thestill sharp-edged stone streets small, but nice homes have been built.  Thearea must still be growing, as you can hear the sounds of constructionechoing from somewhere nearby.  East you can see the `bObsidian way`l as itleads in and out of the city.

This section of the city has recently been built up and paved.  Along thestill sharp-edged stone streets small, but nice homes have been built.  Thearea must still be growing, as you can hear the sounds of constructionechoing from somewhere nearby.  West the neighborhood is much poorer.  Tothe north you see heavy traffic along the `bStreet of Pain`l.  South, thisroad meets the `gStreet of Turquoise`l. ``

To the south is the `dbridge`l that leads out of thecity.  ``

The pavement abruptly ends to the east, where tall `cmaize`l, the mainfood of the city, grows.  Tall stalks rise from the soft, fertile, islandsoil.  The green field stretches away as far as you can see.  It would bevery easy to get lost in there.  To the southwest lies a`h residentialarea`l, and to the north the rounded form of the `oMoon Temple`l dominates.``

The structure's smooth blocks seem to glow with the moon'sown light.  Close by to the north, the entrance of the Plaza of the Moonawaits you.  North and south the street continues, and the busy`d market`lis to the west.  ``

Rooms.RoomName: Jewelled Bird Street and Feathered Serpent Street
Rooms.RoomDescription: This corner of the town is less busy than most.  Most of the pedestriansare black-robed priests, walking with stately stride to their duties.  A fewwarriors have donned odd outfits and head northward, towards a strange Hshaped building.  Westward, Feathered Serpent Street continues, runningbetween the market and the Sun Plaza.  South, Jewelled Bird street extends,running past the Moon Temple.

A muffled, erratic thumping sound comes from the building to the east.The symbols on the door that way show that this is where the ball game isplayed.  The noblest warriors are picked for the teams, and the winners aresacrificed to the gods in the most honorable method possble, thus ensuringthey will be turned into holy eagles in the afterlife.  To the north thereis access to the river, and south the city road leads away.

To the south, a narrow avenue leads into the marketplace.  Mingling withthe smells of fresh tortillas and pulque comes a disquieting scent from thenorthwest.  From there white incense smoke drifts down off of the `kSun`oTemple`l.  Behind it, lies the subtle, deadly smell of fresh blood.  Eastand west `bFeathered Serpent Street`l continues.  ``

The stone pavers are well worn in this busy area of the city.  Norththe wide `oPlaza of the `kSun`l opens, surrounded with fine houses for thepriests.  South of here the busy market place bustles; the entrance to themarket is to the east.  West the neighborhood grows affluent, homes growinglarger and more opulent where clan leaders and noblemen live.``

Rooms.RoomName: Feathered Serpent Street and Eveningstar Road
Rooms.RoomDescription: Eveningstar road begins here, heading to the south.  Along its well wornstones many knights and clan leaders march, gathering somewhere to thesouth.  East the road is very busy with people either shopping or going tothe Sun Temple.  West is a quiet, affluent neigborhood.

The houses here are very fine, larger and better made than any other inthe city.  A fiesta is going on nearby, evidenced by the vibration of lowwooden drums and the shrill squeal of reed pipes.  The sharp smell of peppersauce wafts forth from the celebration.  Homes are north and west, and theroad leads away south.

A proud merchant sweeps past, with a long line of heavily burdenedservants trailing after him.  They head east, into the market.  Eveningstarroad continues north and south.  The west side of the road is entirelyoccupied by the King's Palace.  Its entrance lies to the south.

Directly west lies the entrance to the King's Palace.  Priests, warriors,and clan leaders swarm in and out, coming or going as the king commands.The Palace is by far the nicest, largest home in the city, but it comesnowhere near to the glory of the two temples in the north and east of thecity.  Eveningstar road continues north and south.

On the edge of the path here, a tall, stone statue guards the way.  Itsmouth is agape and its sharpened, stone teeth are ready to rip to shreds anyenemies of the mysterious guardians of this jungle.  A symbol of the sun hasbeen carved into its belly.

Here, and off into the distance eastwardand southward, large, round, white marker stones rest on the edge of thepath.  An image of the fierce and cunning jaguar god has been carved intothe granite stone here.  Just off the path here to the north, a squat stonebuilding has been erected to act as a sentry-post on this well-worn path.

The marketplace is a large area of polished pavement, bordered by shadyarcades, offering shelter to merchants and shoppers alike.  Each quarter ofthe marketplace offers a different type of item.  East of here you seemostly decorative things, and to the west more practical items, like toolsand weapons are offered for sale.

Footsteps ring off the stone pavement, blending into the crowd's constantdin.  All around shoppers mill, a wildly mixed group.  One unfortunateman staggers by, laden with heavy packages while his chattering daughtersfollow behind.North is some sort of interesection.  The path here allows no direct accessto the merchants.

You hear the buzz of voices rise and fall, as all around you peopleengage in quiet but intense bargaining.  To the northeast, food anddrink is sold.  To the southeast you may buy decorative items.Southwest are tools and weapons.  The shipping canal runs through thenorthwest quadrant, making it the perfect place to buy a canoe, and thatis also where the slaves are offered for sale.

A bewlidering variety of wares is offered for sale here, drawing crowdsof shoppers from well beyond this island city.  East is a largeintersection; the crowd seems thickest there.  To the west you can hear andsmell flowing water, where a canal runs through the city.

A group of young men carrying packages pushes past, in a hurry to delivertheir heavy burdens.  They've come from the north, where the shipping dockprovides access to the canal that leads to the river.  Most merchandise isdelivered that way.  West is Eveningstar road and the King's Palace.
Palm trees shade the path, their dark, wide leaves high above, flutteringin the breeze.  Bright colors draw your attention to the south, and thecrowd of shoppers grows more dense to the west.

This is the eastern end of the market plaza.  Further east runs`dJewelled Bird Street `l before the `hM`oo`ho`on `hTemple`l.  West the busy marketbustles, full of merchants and customers- all the necessitites oflife available within.``

Pushing your way through the busy market, the smell of unwashed mendrifts over to you, and you hear a murmur of sullen complaint from the west,where a large crowd has gathered.  To the east you hear sounds of merriment,and several old men wobble past you, laughing.

Barter is the custom here, with the cacao bean somtimes used as astandard.  Although it is strange to them, the merchants seem willing toaccept your foreign gold.  To the east, food and drink is offered forsale.  North you see a busy street passing before the `oTemple of the`kSun`l, which now looms high above you.  ``

The pungent smell of paint is the most noticable thing about thisquiet corner of the market.  Stocked in neat rows, small pots of all thebrightest `jc`ko`ll`mo`nr`is `lare offered for sale here.  Brushes are alsooffered for sale, along with paper, should you wish your work to beportable.  Most of the artists and scribes here work on walls, so the papersits in neglected pile behind the paints.
Tall warriors fill the space around the weapon-maker, excitedly comparingknives, clubs, and spears.  The merchant leans around one man, trying tocatch your eye.  What would you like to see today?

Pottery is a fine art in the `oCity of the `kSun`l, as clearly evidencedby the exquisite pieces on display.  The stand is laden with a bewilderingarray of shapes and colors.  Utilitarian water jugs are as carefully made asthe special ceremonial pieces beside them.

Metal tools are rarely seen in this part of the world, but a few have beenbrought from afar to be offered for sale here.  The `mpink``-`kgold`l shineof beaten copper catches the interest of many a passerby, as the vendorarranges his wears on a blue blanket to make them most attractive.``
A riot of colors fills this corner of the market: you have reached thefeather merchant, who offers both loose bunches of the vibrant plumes, andvarious elegant items, decorated with rarest feathers.

A pair of young girls smile at you with hopeful eyes as you glance overtheir clan's handiwork.  Cotton mantles are offered for sale, some neatlyfolded, while the finest embroidered ones are spread flat for display.

Furniture is not as important to these people as it is in many othercultures, so this corner of the market is not very busy.  But, if you've justbuilt a new house, this would be the ideal place to buy a few essentials.

A crowd has gathered here, admiring the new shipment of jewellry from allacross the lands.  Smiling whispers are exchanged as young women point atbeautiful trinkets.  Next to them a rich warrior bargains earnestly over anexquisite set of `gturquoise`l inlaid earrings.``

Pulque is the fermented juice of the locally grown maguey plant.  Religiousand familial responsibilities disallow most people from becoming intoxicated,but older citizens are free to enjoy themselves.  That would explain the largenumber of drunk old men here, leaning on each other and singing.

You step forward to the `cvegetable`l stand where an old woman squats,grinning over her goods.  Fresh, succulent produce is stacked in symmetricalheaps, protected from the from the pavement by woven reed mats.  The colorfulbounty is tangible evidence that the `ogods`l are pleased this season.``

Rooms.RoomName: A Shady Spot in the Marketplace
Rooms.RoomDescription: `cPalm trees cluster above, providing a cool haven from the bright sun.Vessels holding smaller, flowering plants encircle this corner of themarket, making it secluded and peaceful here- a good spot to enjoy your foodand drink, or rest after a long day of shopping.  ``

With deceptive ease, the tortilla woman grabs a small blob of `kyellow`ldough from her pot, and swiftly pats into a thin round about two feet wide.She tosses this onto a fire-heated stone slab, flipping it over a momentlater, and hands it to a waiting customer.  The tortilla maker's little girltries to imitate her mother, but merely winds up with `kyellow`l goop allover her hands.  ``

A quiet group of onlookers have gathered to appraise the proffered slaves.Some of the chattels wear wooden collars.  The collars and their hopelessexpressions mark some slaves as prisoners of war or crime.  Another group ofslaves is dirty and emaciated, and they look to you with hopeful eyes.  Theseare men who have encounterd misfortune, and are selling themselves to obtainfood and shelter.

The tiles of the ancient, stone floor are covered`awith carvings of spiders,`c snakes`a, and flying creatures.  Between two`alarge,`h granite`a pillars rests a massive altar made from the largest piece of`damber`a you have ever seen.  The rich,`d orange-brown`a altar`k glows`a with some`akind of inner radiance, as does the`d amber`a eyes of the beautiful stone statue`astanding behind it.  The tall statue of the Goddess rests on a three-tiered`apedestal.  Smaller graven images stand on either side of her:  one of a`asnarling`d j`ba`dg`bu`da`br`a and one of an`o eagle`a with a`c snake`a in its talons.  The`areflections of the city's prized`o eternal`k f`il`ka`im`ke`a dance in her`d amber`a eyes,`aproducing an eerie effect.  You suddenly gaze up in alarm and awe at the`aGoddess with the`c wreath`a of`c laurels`a on her head, as you realize that the`asticky substance draining from the`d altar-top`a and dripping from the obsidian`adirks in the statue's unmoving, stone hands, is the`b lifeblood`a of some`aunfortunate creature.  Turning away and turning back again, you could almost`aswear she quickly`o flashed`a you an impish`i grin`a.``

Rooms.RoomDescription: `iYour footsteps echo across the smooth, polished floor of the still, InnerSanctum.  A sense of power can be felt here.  The walls here also have markingson them, much like the other walls within the temple.`hThe etchings upon the smooth, glassy walls describe your last task:"`gBrave one, you have proven your agility in the first task, your intelligencein the second task and your bravery in the third task.  In order to be worthyof the`k Sun God`g it is also necessary to be wise.  The three hallwayswhich branch off of this room lead to either success or failure.The carvings on their walls are in honor of their deities:  `oThe M`ho`oo`hn`oG`ho`od`hd`oe`hs`os`g, the`k Sun God`g and the`i Fire Dancer`g, one of which is always truthful,one is always deceptive and one who is alternately truthful and deceptive butin which order is unknown.  Examine the carvings on the walls in each hallbefore making your choice if you are to succeed.  Determine which door is theone that will lead to success.  Choose wisely.`h"``
`gThe water is sluggish here in the canal.  Bits of debris float and bobaimlessly.  The sound of the busy city can be heard to the east wheremerchants are loading and unloading their wares.

A low, stone building with narrow windows stands here at the edge of thepath to the south.  A small fire pit has been dug here and lined withstones.  From within the wood-lined doorway, voices can be heard.  An evil,hideous statue stands guard here as a warning to all those who are strangersto the`o City of the`k Sun`` `cto leave this place at once.  Dare you enteror should you step back onto the path to the south?  ``

The water here is crowded with traffic, mostly merchants going to or fromthe Market.  Two women on their way to shop spot each other, calling out andwaving.  One of them nearly tipping over a smaller canoe while trying towave her paddle.  The canal extends north to the river.  Back east theshipping dock is even busier with boat traffic.

This large stone-paved plaza is where the residents of the city gather toworsip the `kSun God`l.  The top of the temple pyramid is clearly visiblefrom here, and a set of stairs allows ascent.  North is the entry to theinside of the temple sanctum.  West is a strange circular platform.  To theeast are rows of fine houses, residences of the wealthy- either nobles orpriests.  ``

`gThe walls of this small foyer are encrusted with jewelled mosaic depictingthe various aspects of the `kSun God`g.  In the center of the room is a table,holding a thick pile of folded `hparchment`g.  A polished `bwooden door`g leadsto the sanctuary to the north.  Above the table a golden oil-lamp swings.In its `of`kl`oi`kc`ok`ke`or`ki`on`kg `ol`ki`og`kh`ot`g the mosaic gods seem to come to life.  Yes... didn'tthe eyes move on the figure with the feathered mask?``

`nAs you hold up your light, the enclosing walls of `othick translucentalabaster `g `nare revealed.  The room is awesomely large, the ceiling so high itfades away into darkness.  Almost entirely bare, the Inner Sanctum holds onlyone item.  In the center of the room stands a `k`dsolid gold pedestal `n witha small item atop it.  A closer look reveals the famed icon of the`m`jHummingbird Wizard `n`n- the `kSun God`n`c`n, whom this temple is devoted to.The `iicon`n was found along the river bank by the founders of this cityLegends say that the icon keeps its owner safe and can answer anyquestion posed to it.``

You stand in the center of a huge, round `hstone`l platform.  Below your feetthe carven image of the `ksun`l is visible.  In ever-widening circles, shapes ofplanets, stars, and gods surround you.  Vile, dark brown stains besmirch thefine carvings.  Nearby, row after row of human skulls have been fastenedtogether, forming a hideous altar.  Looking back down, it seems odd that thebloodstains are all so old.  `jAs if there hasn't been a sacrifice here in awhile...``

Looking to the top of the `kSun `oTemple`l you notice that the ascentseems endless- the angle of the stairs is such that you cannot see the top.The stairway is wide enough for ten to walk abreast, easily.  Each stair isknee-high, making progress quite strenuous.  Down below chimes ring andflutes whistle, calling the people to worship.  ``

Rooms.RoomName: A Plateau on the Temple Pyramid
Rooms.RoomDescription: Here a wide terrace cuts into the side of the temple pyramid, forming awide plateau.  A few small stone sheds house the on-duty priests.  Stairslead both up and down, fearsome serpent heads terminating the balustradesbordering each stairway.

The angle is still so steep that the top remains hid from sight.  Downbelow a crowd has gathered to witness this hour's sacrifice to the sun.Priests in full ceremonial garb swarm past you, in a hurry to reach the top.

The top of the `kSun `oTemple `ltowers high above the city, allowing aclear view of the entire island.  To ensure that the sun will risetomorrow morning, the priests are making a sacrifice of human blood.Captive after captive has been cut open, their blood running down thetemple's back to stain the river below.``

This room is where the family gathers for social occasions, as well asbeing the way in and out of the house.  Small windows punctuate the thickearthen walls, providing some sunlight.  The floor is of stone, but brightlycolored rugs add softness and comfort.  Woven mats are provided for seatingalongside small wooden tables.

The scent of beans and peppers wafts from the steaming pot heatingover the corner fireplace.  Wooden benches and tables have been set up,ready for the upcoming meal.  Among the plates and dishes a few iconshave been scattered in the hopes that the gods bless the meal.

Small and plain, this room is where the slaves sleep and spend their raretimes off.  Woven mats and a few blankets are the the most prominent items,among a few shabby belongings scattered about.  A single oil lamp hangs fromthe ceiling, augmenting with its flickering glow the meagre daylight from thewindow slit.

Comfortable looking sleeping mats cover the floor, with thick cottonblankets provided should the night have a chill.  The largest window in thehouse is here, overlooking the central courtyard.  On the window-sill a small`cgreen lizard`l `ksuns`l itself, always keeping an eye pointed your direction.``

`cThe central couryard is open to the `nsky`c, providing light and air to all thesurrounding rooms, along with a private garden space for the family to enjoy.Gravel covers the ground, decorated with a few plants.  A small trellis isnearly lost under a lush flowering vine, where a tiny yellow bird hops amongthe green leaves.``

Tiny flowers grow here in a rainbow of colors.  Tropical birds gracefullyfly past you, chirping a variety of musical notes.  A cool, refreshingbreeze blows through the trees and you hear a nearby rustle.  That was thewind, wasn't it?

Tiny flowers grow here in a rainbow of colors.  Tropical birds gracefullyfly past you, chirping a variety of musical notes.  A cool, refreshingbreeze blows through the trees and you hear a nearby rustle.  That was thewind, wasn't it?

The canopy of towering trees draws closed high above you.  Sun filteringthrough the leaves tints the air green.  With each step you hear rustlingmovement all around you, as wild creatures scurry to get out of your way.

The thick, dense foliage can not be pierced by your gaze.  Tall treestower overhead, veiling the bright, hot sun and creating a kaleidoscope ofgreens upon the jungle floor.  A rustle in the nearby underbrush instantlysets you on your guard.

The scent of fish from the docks not far off to the west, greets you inthis recently built section of town.  The sound of on-going construction canbe heard nearby.  Close by to the west, stately`b Eveningstar Road`l begins.

Small, quaint homes line both sides of the street in this middle-classsection of the city.  Due to the constant growth here, the sounds ofconstruction: the heavy thump of mallets and the coarse sound of grindingstones are a familiar part of this section of town.

Oil-soaked torches illumine this this windowless foyer.  The smoothplastered walls have been completely covered with painted scenes.  Most ofthe colorful murals show the King in battle- defeating all the surroundingtribes.  A few show the gods favoring the City of the Sun or the variousclan leaders dressed for war.

`jThe `fKing's Garden`j is so large that an arrow shot from one side wouldnot reach the opposite wall.  Manicured wilderness mimics the jungle, gravelpaths offering ease of travel.  Tame parrots chatter and pet monkeys swingdown to play.  Stone archways with carven symbols above are barely visible,afar off, set into all four of the garden walls.  West, a `er`fi`bs`li`nn`og `ksun`jindicates the residence of the king.  South a `if`me`oa`mt`ih`me`or`me`id `ms`oe`mr`ip`me`on`mt`j signifiespriests.  An `deagle`j to the north stands for warriors.  East a `bbasket`j showsthe way out.

Weapons and armor and supplies of all sorts are stored here- offerings ofall the clan leaders to the king.  Mostly the arms are used to attacksurrounding villages, to capture sacrificial victims.  However, if someother power should arise and mount an assault, with all this the king wouldbe amply prepared.

`gThe rooftop of the `fKing's Palace`g offers a clear view of theriver to the west and the busy market place to the east.  Warriorsrepresenting the various local clans serve their turn at guarding the King'shome, each trying to out-do the rest with the richness of their dress andtheir prowess in arms.  ``

Not even thin woven mats soften the stone floor of the priests' wing.These men are here to show their dedication to serving the gods, in pain andblood and self-sacrifice.  Most have ritually mutilated themselves invariously hideous ways.  A few of the weaker ones have fallen asleep on thestones, earning the scorn of the rest.

The Clan Chiefs have gathered, called by the king to prepare a raid on anearby village which has been neglectful of its tribute.  Each clan leaderwears a bright mask with the likeness of an animal upon it, along withbrilliant embroidered cotton armor and colorful feathers.

Guests of the King stay here during visits.  Currently a delegation ofclan chiefs has been summoned, so the rooms are cluttered with jewelry,weapons, and emblems of rank.  Thick mats and plush carpets have beenprovided for the noble guest's comfort.
This long, low dining hall is hushed at the moment.  Quiet slaves moveabout, setting up for the next meal.  It looks like 200 people could eathere easily.

The kitchen is a bustle of activity as the cooks prepare a feast for thegathered clan chiefs.  Roaring cook fires make the room uncomfortably warm.The mingled scents of smoke and food weigh heavily in the air.

The throne room is just that, a large plain room with a single object-the king's throne, slightly raised on a small dais.  The clan chiefs haveremoved all ornament before entering, so as to not outshine the simple garbworn by their War Chief who sits upon the throne.

The walls of this chamber have been hung with fresh, sweetly scentedflowers- complementing perfectly the array of beautiful young women within:the King's wives.  Off to the back of the room a terrace leads to a swimmingpool where many of the women splash and laugh.

Meagre wispsof straw line the floor, offering only a remembrance of comfort.  Vile smellsof sick and unwashed people fill the stuffy hut.  There is not even a tinywindow to provide light or air.``

Rooms.RoomDescription: Green and tall, maize, the main food of the city, grows nearby here.  Faroff to the north, the massive, circular-shaped walls of the`o Moon Temple```lcapture the attention of passing visitors to the city.  To the west liesthe recently built`h residential area`l.  ``

`dThe scent of sewage behind this old section of the city fills the airhere like a fog.  Low, mud covered houses stand in various states ofdisrepair.  A cloud of flies buzz in a thick mist to the west.  Close by tothe east, the newly constructed`b Eveningstar Road`d stretches from north tosouth.  ``

Nearby to the west, a vast sea of green grows.  `k Maize`l -- thelifeblood of the People of the Sun is painstakingly cultivated and storedfor the city.  The massive, gleaming stone walls of the`o Moon Temple`ltower over the corn, symbolically filling it with the goodness and blessingof the`o Moon God`l.  ``

This part of Eveningstar Road is always bustling with activity.Priestesses and healers pass by here frequently to heal the poor in thenearby slums.  Many from the new residential area pass by daily to purchasefood and draw water from the marketplace to the east.  Nearby to the north,fresh warriors walk through the palace entrance to relieve those standinglong hours guarding the King.

`lThe gleaming stone walls of the hallowed,`o M`ho`oo`hn`o T`he`om`hp`ol`he`l rise to awe passersby.`lA solemn air radiates from the silent temple entrance to the east, shutting`lout the usual bustle the city's many carpenters, priests, merchants and`lwarriors.  Northward and Southward, Jewelled Bird Street stretches on as far`las the eye can see.``

A proud merchant sweeps past, with a long line of heavily burdenedservants trailing after him.  They head east, into the market.  Eveningstarroad continues north and south.  The west side of the road is entirelyoccupied by the King's Palace.  Its entrance lies to the south.

To the southeast, the gleaming shape of the`o Moon Temple`l rises,filling passersby with awe.  To the north and south, Jewelled Bird Streetstretches as far as the eye can see.  Close by to the North, FeatheredSerpent Street begins.  ``

Walked over by thousands of feet over several years, the stones of thisstreet are worn down to a smooth, dull finish.  Priests, priestesses, clanleaders, warriors and other important people enter the`k Plaza of the Sun`lto the northeast, to consult the High Priest on a daily basis about variousday-to-day matters.

Few people pass by this quiet section of the city.  Priests occassionallypass by to enter the`k Plaza of the Sun`l nearby.  Warriors dressed instrange garb travel eastward towards Jewelled Bird Street.  ``

`cThe tasks have been completed and the powerful Hummingbird Wizard has beendefeated.  The mysteries of the`k City of the Sun`c have been left behind inthe awe-inspiring`o Moon Temple`c.  On the top of this hill one can see theentire city laid out before them:  from the gorgeous royal palace far off tothe west, the tall gateway to the south, to the calm, aquamarine strip of oceanjust on the horizon to the east.  Descend the hill to re-enter the city onJewelled Bird Street.

This large, paved expanse is towered over by the pyramid temple of theGreat `kSun God`l.  Priests, priestesses, adepts, warriors, nobles and clanleaders alike, congregate here all during the day to worship at the templepyramid.  Northward, a steep set of stone stairs lead up to the summit ofthis awe inspiring momument.  To the south, Feathered Serpent Streetstretches from east to west.

Cheers and less pleasant sounds can be heard echoing somewhere nearbythis quiet corner of town.  Northeasterly, in the direction of the faintcries, a large, H-shaped building can be seen.  To the north, the streetcontinues on to end at the swift moving jungle river.  Close by to thesouth, the street intersects with famed Feathered Serpent Street.

`nCheers and other less pleasant sounds can be heard echoing from theball court spectators, as well as grunts and yelled orders from the teamscurrently on the court.  The door to the east here leads directly onto thedangerous playing field and the heavily travelled path to the west leads toJewelled Bird Street.``

The quiet and sometimes dangerous waters of the Great River gently lap atthe end of this path.  Women can be seen nearby bathing in the tall reeds.Downstream, others can be seen slapping wet clothing against smoothriverstones to get them clean.  Faint sounds resembling cheering echo overthe calm waters from the southeast.  South of here begins Jewelled SerpentStreet of the legendary`k City of the Sun`l.  ``

Torchlight flickers above a dark pit here.  To the west of this narrowroom a crack in the stone wall can be seen.  To the south, the open doorwayleads to the entrance to the sentry post at the front of the city.  Theguards playing with bone dice here suddenly look up at you with surprise ontheir faces and demand to know how you got in here.  Since only guards areallowed inside the sentry post they label you a spy and force you down intothe pit on a ladder made of hemp.

A heavy stone slab quickly slides into place, sealing off the way youcame in.  There is nothing special about this bare, stone room, except for alarge crack in the floor near one of the room's corners from where a faintbreeze seems to be issuing forth.

Canoes an small punts of all shapes and sizes have been tied up here.Some are being loaded or unloaded with merchandise, some are merely tied andwaiting for their owners.  A few have bright ink-marks splashed on theirnear sides, indicating they are for sale.  A canal running throught the cityis accessible to the west, and the market place is back to the east.

Canoes are highly prized by the people of this island city, so only a feware ever offered for sale.  Perhaps if you're lucky, one will be availabletoday and you can explore the vibrant tropical river.  The boat seller sitson an overturned old canoe, using an obsidian blade to shave away curls froma block of white wood with an obsidian knife, lost in thought as he carvesperfect toy canoes.  A little noise might capture his attention.

`mYou stand at one end of a long hallway inside the `oMoon Temple`m.Polished obsidian floor stretches away before you.  The walls are smooth,and freshly painted with pictures that seem to tell a story.  Wooden doorsinterrupt the storyline at parts, and the doors themselves have carvingsall over them.  ``

`gLooking west, you see a story told in the painted pictures these peopleuse.  Somehow, after looking a moment, it begins to make sense...`kIn the first age, called `dFour Ocelot`k both men and giants walked the landsThe lord of all was the Smoking Mirror, the Chief of the Gods.  The menof that age failed in their duties, and the world came to ruin - Jaguarsoverran all, devouring the men and giants.  To bring life to the next age, theSmoking Mirror turned himself into the sun.  `dFour Ocelot`k ended and`nFour Wind`k began.```g    To the south a wooden door also tells a story.``

`gOnce again you stand in the obsidian-floored hallway in the interior ofthe Moon Temple.  Something grips you here, keeping you from going anywhere`gbut through the door to your north.  Looking east, the story of the four suns```gcontinues...`kAs the second sun shone over the world, the `iF`me`oa`mt`ih`me`or`me`id `mS`oe`mr`ip`me`on`mt`k- Lord of thesky - ruled over all.  Once again the men of that age neglected theirobligations.  Hurricanes came and destroyed the world, and all the men wereturned into monkeys.  `nFour Wind `kended and `lFour Rain`k began.`g     A door to the north has important information on it.``

`gYou return to the cool, glittering hallway within the`o Moon Temple`g. The`gcompulsion on you only allows you to leave through the door southward.  Thestory continues on the west wall...`lIn the third age the `aRain God`l gave the world light.  When he was not fedas needed his providence came to an end.  A fiery rain fell, annihilatingall.  Four Rain was no more - `nFour Water `lreplaced it.```g     Another message awaits your perusal upon the southern door.``

`gYou have reached the end of the obsidian-floored hall within the `oMoonTemple`g.  A compelling force draws you forward, towards the door to the`geast.  Blazing in bright colors, the walls about you tell a story...```mIn the time of `lFour Water `m- the age just preceeding our own- `gOur Ladyof the Turquoise Skirt`m, the Goddess of Water ruled over all.  Whenthe ending of the Fourth Sun came, floods laid waste to the world, and all themen were turned into fish. Our time of `iFour Earthquake`m began.```gUpon the door are further instructions.``

`gThe priestesses of the `mFlower Bird`g surround you.  Deft, small handswrap a blindfold about your eyes.  More hands gently lead you forth, guidingcarefully your blind steps.  On and on, through twists and turns - all senseof direction fails you.  The sounds of the city fade away far behind.  Witha gentle tug the priestesses urge you to step downwards.  ``

`oThe priestesses remove your blindfold.  You find yourself standing inthe midst of a vast jungle.  Next to you stands a massive tree, dwarfing`oeven the typically gigantic jungle trees.  A sturdy towering vine windsaround and up the massive trunk.  The priestesses bow, and walk away,vanishing into the greenery.  When you have slain the jaguar return herewith its skin to proceed to your next task.``

The warm water of the river gently flows here.  What appears to be arotting log slowly floating along the current suddenly turns into acrocodile as it slowly heaves itself up the heavily foliated banks.  Thegentle current flows from the south to the east here.  A tall, stone pyramidcan be seen peeking over the treetops in the distance.

The slow, calm waters of the Great River meander from the west to thesouth.  A gentle breeze refreshingly blows and the crowing from a flock ofbirds can be heard as they lift off in flight from a nearby tree.

A foul stench rises from the water here.  To the north you see its cause:a stone channel empties all the city's sewage into the river water.  Poormud hovels crowd together near the outlet.  Clearly, this edge of the cityis the worst place to live.  To the east the river is choked with mud and athick mat of jungle debris, making further travel that way impossible.
